"{\"uid\": \"thesouthafrican.com-sport-paris-olympics-2024-must-see-whale-breaches-during-paris-olympics-surfing-in-tahiti-picture-image-breaking\", \"text\": \"Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.  thesouthafrican.com is a division of Blue Sky Publications Ltd. Reproduction without permission prohibited  Home\\u00bbSport\\u00bbParis Olympics 2024\\u00bbMUST SEE: Whale breaches during Paris Olympics surfing in Tahiti  A whale jumped out of the water during the\\u00a0Paris Olympics 2024 surfing competition in Teahupo'o, Tahiti on Monday. Take a look!  Awhalejumped out of the water during theParis Olympics 2024surfing competition in Teahupo'o, Tahiti on Monday, offering spectators a moment of enchantment.  Enjoy the Paris Olympic Games 2024 experience at your favourite ATKV Resort!  With all eyes on the ocean during the final day of the Paris Olympics surfing\\u00a0competition in Tahiti on Monday afternoon, a surprise guest made an appearance: a whale.  A safe distance from athletes Tatiana Weston-Webb from\\u00a0Brazil\\u00a0and Brisa Hennessy of Costa Rica - who were competing in a semi-final match - the whale breached and gave spectators and photographers the Olympic moment of a lifetime.  For the latest Paris Olympics 2024 news, bookmarkThe South African website'sdedicated section for free-to-read content  It's not uncommon for wild animals such as birds, seals and even\\u00a0sharks\\u00a0to appear while surfing around the world.  In Tahiti, where the 2024 Olympics surfing competition was held almost 10 000 miles away from the host city of Paris, whales gather around the islands during mating, birthing and migration season.  Tahiti also has several maritime protected zones.  In April, Pacific Indigenous leaders - including some from Tahiti - signed a treaty recognising\\u00a0whales as \\\"legal persons,\\\" although such a declaration is not reflected in the laws of participating nations.  WIN R2 000: Take The South African's SASSA Survey  The South African is hiring! Freelance writing positions available  Follow The South African on Facebook for the latest local and international news  Follow The South African's WhatsApp channel for the latest sport, lifestyle and local news  Follow The South African on X for the latest, breaking news  A brand new shopping mall is coming to Pretoria East, bringing major retailers and new convenience to the area.  Orlando Pirates are reportedly set to welcome a new staff member in former Stellenbosch FC Head of Recruitment Brendon Fourie.  Masindi Nemtajela was stretched off during Orlando Pirates' 6-0 win over TS Galaxy on Sunday afternoon in Mbombela.  IT support is not just technical, it is personal.  Liema Pantsi's victory was clouded as fans of the 'Big Brother Mzansi' show expressed that Smash Afrika was unprofessional towards her.  A dominant weekend for the SA teams in the URC has made a big impact on the latest log standings as the playoffs edge closer.    TheSouthAfrican.com is all about South Africa and the stories that affect South Africans, wherever they are in the world.  We are independent.No agenda.No bias.  Our offices are for administrative purposes only, no visitors will be accepted without an appointment.  South Africa- Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd - Registration Number: 2005/028472/07 - Address: Regus Business Centre, 1st Floor, Block B, North Park, Black River Park, 2 Fir Street, Observatory, Cape Town, 7925, South Africa  Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.\"}"